                </ul>

                <p class="span5">
                    Salamina, Aegina, the peninsula of Methana, Agkistri, Poros, Spetses, Hydra form the island complex of the Argosaronic Gulf in southern Greece.
                    Sprinkled over the Argosaronic Gulf and steeped in ancient mythology, these islands are small havens in close proximity to Athens.
                    Daily ferry connection from the port of Piraeus makes them a lovely, easily accessible all-year-round destination for the Athenians.
                    Visitors here will enjoy natural beauty, historical treasures, unique architecture, and glamorous, yet romantic atmosphere.
                </p>

                <h4 class="span8">Sounion</h4>
                <ul class="span3 list-thumbnail">
                    <li>
                        <a href="http://www.visitgreece.gr/en/nature/forests/sounio_national_park" target="_blank" class="thumbnail">
                            <%= image_tag 'guide/sounion_posidon_temple.jpg' %>
                            <p class="attribution">photo by Belyshev CC BY-SA 3.0</p>
                        </a>
                    </li>
                </ul>

                <p class="span5">
                    Cape Sounion is located 69 kilometres (43 miles) southeast of Athens, at the southernmost tip of the Attica peninsula.
                    It is noted as the site of ruins of the ancient Greek temple of Poseidon, the god of the sea in classical mythology.
                    The remains are perched on the headland, surrounded on three sides by the sea.
                    The site is a popular day-excursion for tourists from Athens, with sunset over the Aegean Sea, as viewed from the ruins.
                </p>

